(218, 1, '2015-01-06 12:26:03', '2015-01-06 12:26:03', '<div class="main_heading full_width">\r\n  <h1 class="red_color ">Repaired and Rebuilt Our Roads</h1>\r\n  <div class="main_headingBorder"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="blue_text_container full_width top_margin">\r\n  <div class="inner_blue_container">\r\n    <p class="btm_padding">For years, Columbus underinvested in maintaining\r\nits roads.  When Mayor Kristen Brown assumed office, we were far behind schedule and many of our streets werein total disrepair, creating difficult and unsafe driving conditions and wear and tear on our vehicles.Mayor Brown made our most critical infrastructure  a top priority and under her leadership, the City of Columbus has:</p>\r\n    \r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class="img_container"><img src="images/roads.png"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="inner_text_container full_width top_margin">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Completed the largest road repair project in the citys history by investing an unprecedented $10 million to reconstruct and resurface 40 miles of crumbling streets.</li>\r\n<li>Completed or began six major road improvement projects for a combined investment of $20 million.</li>\r\n<li>Completed the largest road repair project in the citys history, investing an unprecedented $10 million in three years to reconstruct and resurface approximately 40 miles of crumbling streets.  By comparison the City was spending less than $400,000 repaving only about 4 miles of roads a year prior to her assuming the job of mayor in 2012.</li>\r\n<li>Completed construction or begun the design of six major road improvement projects for a combined investment of more than $20 million funded primarily by federal transportation dollars.</li>\r\n<li>Fourth Street  this $2.2 million in 2012 project transformed 4th Street from Jackson to Lafayette.  Its now pedestrian friendly, accommodates expanded outdoor seating and is readily closed to traffic for community events and celebrations.</li>\r\n<li>200S  this $3 million project in 2013 alleviated traffic congestion and made this old country road, now a suburban collector, significantly safer for motorists, school buses and pedestrians by widening the lanes, adding a left-turn lane, a storm sewer system, a sidewalk and railroad crossing improvements.</li>\r\n<li>Carr Hill Road  this $2.2 million in 2014 project transformed this formercountry road into a suburban collector to better serve the growing residential area on the west side of Columbus. The improved street provide wider traffic lanes, curbs, gutters, storm sewers, bicycle lanes and sidewalks on both sides of the street.</li>\r\n<li>Indiana Avenue  this $7 million project in 2015 will improve this suburban collector serving Columbus East High School and connecting two arterials, Marr Road and State Street, on Columbus east side.  Lanes will be widened and a storm sewer system, bicycle lanes and sidewalks will be added.  Currently the utility relocation is complete and construction will be \r\ncompleted this year.</li>\r\n<li>Rocky Ford Taylor to Talley  this $7 million project in 2016 will transform this old country road into a suburban collector.  It includes widened lanes in each direction, a two-way left turn lane, bicycle lanes, a storm sewer system and sidewalks on both sides of the street. The City is currently acquiring right-of-way for this project and construction is planned in 2016.</li>\r\n<li>Maple Street  this $1 million project will extend Maple Street from Tipton Lane to U.S. 31, giving pedestrians, bicyclists and motorists significantly safer routes and alleviating traffic congestion to and from school in the four-school campus area that includes Columbus North High School, Northside Middle School, Schmitt Elementary School and St. Bartholomew Catholic \r\nSchool. The City is currently in the design engineering phase of this project and construction is planned in 2016.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Roads', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '166-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-01-06 12:26:03', '2015-01-06 12:26:03', '', 166, 'http://localhost/brown-for-columbus/166-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
